{{Infobox glacier | child = | name = Aviator Glacier | other_name = | photo = C73193s5 Ant.Map Mount Murchison.jpg | photo_width = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = 1:250,000 scale topographic map of the Aviator Glacier and the [[Southern Cross Mountains]] | map = Antarctica | map_width = | map_alt = | map_caption = Location of Aviator Glacier in [[Antarctica]] | mark = Blue_pog.svg | type = | location = [[Victoria Land]] | coordinates = {{coord|73|50|S|165|03|E|region:AQ|format=dms|display=inline}} | coords_ref = | area = | length = {{convert|96|km|mi|abbr=on}} | width = {{convert|8|km|mi|abbr=on}} | thickness = unknown | elevation_max = | elevation_min = | terminus = [[Lady Newnes Bay]] | status = unknown | embedded = }}
'''Aviator Glacier''' is major valley glacier in Antarctica that is over {{convert|60|mi|km}} long and {{convert|5|mi|km}} wide, descending generally southward from the plateau of [[Victoria Land]] along the west side of [[Mountaineer Range]], and entering [[Lady Newnes Bay]] between [[Cape Sibbald]] and [[Hayes Head]] where it forms the '''Aviator Glacier Tongue'''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Find the Data |title=Glacier: Aviator Glacier, Antarctica |url=http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/532/Aviator-Glacier |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701114303/http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/532/Aviator-Glacier |dead-url=yes |archive-date=1 July 2012 |accessdate=10 May 2012 }}</ref>
A glacier is a mass of ice with sufficient thickness to flow away from the source area in lobes, tongues or masses. Glaciers are usually found at high altitudes or high elevations.<ref>{{cite web |last= TravelsRadiate |title= Aviator Glacier Tongue |url= http://www.travelsradiate.com/antarctica/antarctica/6635495-aviator-glacier-tongue.html |accessdate= 10 May 2012 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20120914072642/http://www.travelsradiate.com/antarctica/antarctica/6635495-aviator-glacier-tongue.html |archivedate= 14 September 2012 |df= }}</ref>
The glacier was photographed from the air by Captain W.M. Hawkes, [[US Navy]], on the historic first flight from New Zealand to [[McMurdo Sound]] on December 17, 1955. An attempt to reconnoiter it by helicopter and to land a party of the NZGSAE on it had to be abandoned when USS ''Glacier'' was damaged in pressure ice in December 1958. Named by NZGSAE, 1958–59, as a tribute to the hazardous work of pilots and other airmen in Antarctic exploratory and scientific operations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Find the Data |title=Glacier: Aviator Glacier, Antarctica |url=http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/532/Aviator-Glacier |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120701114303/http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/532/Aviator-Glacier |dead-url=yes |archive-date=1 July 2012 |accessdate=10 May 2012 }}</ref>
==Aviator Glacier Tongue== The Aviator Glacier Tongue in Antarctica is a seaward extension of Aviator Glacier into the Ross Sea, between Wood Bay and Lady Newness Bay along the coast of Victoria Land.<ref>{{cite web|last=Find the Data |title=Glacier: Aviator Glacier Tongue, Antarctica |url=http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/533/Aviator-Glacier-Tongue |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709045847/http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/533/Aviator-Glacier-Tongue |dead-url=yes |archive-date=9 July 2012 |accessdate=10 May 2012 }}</ref> This floating [[ice tongue]] extends into the water for about {{convert|25|km|mi|0}}. The name was recommended by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in association with Aviator Glacier.<ref>{{cite web|last=Find the Data |title=Glacier: Aviator Glacier Tongue, Antarctica |url=http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/533/Aviator-Glacier-Tongue |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120709045847/http://antarctica-geography.findthedata.org/l/533/Aviator-Glacier-Tongue |dead-url=yes |archive-date=9 July 2012 |accessdate=10 May 2012 }}</ref>
